      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 42-year-old patient with a history of episodic muscle weakness and abnormal sensations is undergoing neurological evaluation. The neurologist, suspecting an underlying ion channelopathy. A thorough understanding of the ions responsible for the resting membrane potential (RMP) is crucial for pinpointing the diagnosis and formulating an effective treatment plan. </span><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\">Which of the following ions have equilibrium potential close to the resting membrane potential in the neurons and is responsible for its RMP?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7324336",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33621,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. B) Potassium</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Potassium (K+) ions</strong> have an <strong>equilibrium potential</strong> close to the <strong>resting membrane</strong> potential of <strong>neurons</strong>, around <strong>-70 mV</strong>. The <strong>high permeability</strong> of <strong>neuronal membranes</strong> to <strong>K+ ions</strong> due to <strong>numerous K+</strong> <strong>leak channels</strong> largely sets the <strong>RMP</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\">The <strong>resting membrane potential (RMP)</strong> of the <strong>neurons</strong> will be <strong>around -70 mV</strong> (more negative inside) under physiological conditions</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\">This potential will be near/ <strong>CLOSE TO </strong>the equilibrium potential for the <strong>POTASSIUM </strong>ions and <strong>EQUAL TO</strong> the equilibrium potential for <strong>CHLORIDE&nbsp;</strong></span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Sodium (Na+) ions</strong> have an <strong>equilibrium potential</strong> far more <strong>positive</strong> than the <strong>resting membrane potential</strong>, primarily contributing to action potentials rather than the RMP.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Calcium (Ca2+) ions</strong> have an equilibrium potential much <strong>more positive</strong> than the <strong>RMP</strong> and are more involved in <strong>neurotransmitter release</strong> and <strong>muscle contractions</strong> than in setting the RMP.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Chloride (Cl-) K+ ions</strong> are primarily responsible for the <strong>RMP</strong>(Not chloride) due to their <strong>relative permeability</strong> and <strong>concentration gradient</strong>. RMP of Neuron is <strong>EQUAL</strong> to (Not close to) <strong>equilibrium potential</strong> of <strong>chloride</strong>, but the K+ is the main ion responsible for it, so the RMP is <strong>NEAR</strong> to the equilibrium potential of K+.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\">To understand the <strong>pivotal role</strong> of <strong>potassium (K+) ions</strong> in establishing the <strong>resting membrane</strong> <strong>potential</strong> in <strong>neurons</strong>, foundational for <strong>neural excitability</strong> and function.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref: Ganong's Review of Medical physiology 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 90</strong></span></p>",
